We must “total‐up” only those transactions whose type indicates an expense of the business (not funding contributions, purchases, sales, interest receivable, etc). In our data the expense items are the rows whose “type” string starts with “Expense…” and also the single “Depreciation” transaction (which is an expense).

Here is how one may do it step‐by‐step (note that the “amount” column is used):

1. Skip the “Initial…” (cash, bank, fixed assets) and “Purchase…” and “Sale…” items as well as the “Interest Receivables” (they are not “expenses” on the income statement).

2. Keep only rows whose type is “Expense…” (for example “Administrative Expenses”, “Sales Expenses”, “Financial Expenses”) and also include the “Depreciation” row.
